The Nigerian Institute of Public Relations (NIPR) has identified non-adoption of strategic crisis management communication as a major impediment in the fight against the Coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic. In a statement signed by its national President and Chairman, Governing Council, Mukhtar Zubairu Sirajo, NIPR commended the efforts being made by the federal and state governments, the COVID-19 Taskforce, organisations and well meaning Nigerians, but noted that the non-inclusion of critical stakeholders, especially communication and public relations experts was counter-productive. NIPR is of the view that If synergy is improved and the efforts are better coordinated, Nigeria will again rise to the occasion in no time as was the case with Ebola. It said, “The medical dimension of COVID-19 is no doubt the spindle around which the wheel revolves, but the pandemic has assumed a monumental proportion and so requires strategic crisis communication in handling the situation. “This is because it does not require only public enlightenment, but also crafting of appropriate messages, networking with other stakeholders as well as analysis of the pros and cons of measures to be taken as they affect segments of the society.” Citing the concerns expressed by Nigerians, especially the Nigerian Medical Association (NMA) over the involvement of Chinese medical personnel in tackling the disease in Nigeria, the institute said the dust it raised was a fallout of communication and enlightenment gap. The institute however said it would continue to support the effort of government and all concerned groups and individuals involved in providing timely and sustainable solution to situation. It said in solidarity with government in the fight against the dreaded global disease, it had earlier closed its offices around the country and suspended all its programmes forthwith until situation improves.